The efficiency of transmission was assessed by calculating the proportion of contact animals that contracted infection, considering only cages in which donor guinea pigs were productively infected through intranasal inoculation. While transmission occurred in 7/9 instances for PR8 NL09 M virus, a significantly lower proportion of animals (1/20; p<0.0001) were infected with a virus carrying an avian M segment transmitted from her cage mate (

  Fig 3B
 ). Thus, data from a mammalian animal model reveal defects in infectivity, growth and transmission associated with avian IAV M segments. Our results suggest the acquisition of adaptive changes in the M segment of pH1N1 human IAV since its introduction from the avian reservoir into mammals.
